      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:37:28.278463+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "6b97a4e8",
      "step_index": 9,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Features decreasing likelihood of CYP2D6 inhibition specifically:**\n- **Lack of a strongly basic, protonatable amine** near the aromatic system. CYP2D6 inhibition is strongly enriched for compounds with a cationic center at physiological pH (classic \u201cbasic N + aromatic\u201d pharmacophore).\n- The **hydrazide/amide** functionality tends to **lower basicity** and can increase polarity/H-bonding in a way that may reduce the classic CYP2D6 ionic interaction and sometimes reduces passive partitioning into the hydrophobic pocket (though your molecule still has substantial lipophilicity from the rings/CF3).",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:37:28.278484+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "147a7e2a",
      "step_index": 10,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "## 3) Mechanistic basis (interaction with CYP2D6)",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:37:28.278506+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "4cecae6f",
      "step_index": 11,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "- **Typical strong CYP2D6 inhibitors**: bind with a **protonated amine** forming a salt bridge/ionic interaction with **Asp301**, plus aromatic stacking in the active site.\n- This molecule likely binds (if at all) more like a **neutral, hydrophobic CYP ligand** (\u03c0/van der Waals driven), which can inhibit some CYPs, but is **less characteristic** of potent CYP2D6 inhibition because it may not engage the key Asp301 interaction efficiently.\n- Could still show **some inhibition** via occupancy/competitive binding due to aromatic bulk, but the **signature 2D6 pharmacophore is weak** here.",
